segments.text: It was Alan Shivers, as I recall, at the time.
And then, of course, any time we had two or three generals come to the campus, we acted as the honor guard for.
And there was no malarkey, no pranks or jokes.
No.
About RVs.
No.
And as far as you know, the selection
always was on the basis of quality.
I assume because I didn't have any friends.
I mean anybody that, you know, I don't know how they picked them.
During your years at A&M, who were the notable campus administrators?
Well, let's see.
We had, you remember the freshmen were under the basic division and it was, the dean was Bertram.
Was that who it was?
I'm not sure.
It was the dean of the basic division.
I think it was Bertram or Bertrand.
Of course, we had two presidents, Harrington and Morgan.
Morgan came in my junior year.
Eide Trotter.
Eide P. Trotter.
Abbott.
John Paul Abbott.
Bolton.
Bear Tracks Bolton.
Was Pinky Downs?
Oh, he and his daughter are still there, all over the campus, yeah.
What did you all think of Pinky?
I just thought he was a nice guy.
I wondered why he was spending his life doing what he was doing there.
He didn't do anything that I know of.
I don't know what he did.
He was the official greeter.
That's what I said.
And apparently, I'm putting two and two together and getting 4,000.
He had been on the board of directors back in the 20s as a young man and then during the Depression or soon thereafter his bank went broke and apparently this was to give him something to do.
Is that what it was?
Yeah.
Like we never saw him sad.
He was always upbeat and positive.
And he was all over the campus, you know.
Who were the, as you look back, who were your closest buddies?
They were always people in my outfit, people from here that stayed.
Aggie friendships last, don't they?
Oh, yeah.
Why?
I don't know, but I mean, you just build a relationship with them.
And in your major, were there some teachers that were really, as you looked?
Oh, I had some magnificent professors.
You know, they were more than just professors.
They were interested in you.
I had, as I said, what was his name?
Was it Norman Rose?
Mm-hmm.
Dillingham, Hallmark.
I didn't know him.
Hughes, who was head of the department at the time, I didn't know him that well.
Mike, what was his name, Albert Drews, great guy.
What were some of the courses that were for you later you realized were important?
Oh, I think the courses that I had my senior year and in graduate school were probably very important.
I think the basic courses that I took probably in my sophomore year, freshman, sophomore year, and then the graduate school courses,

is it look in hindsight is there anything that a m didn't do or is there any area of your uh profession that maybe didn't get enough attention well i don't think i think a m gave me for what i did i think texas a m one instilled in me as i said

the ability to pursue to keep at it never give up I think to be I think to work hard I studied harder than I'd ever studied in my life and I think that that in itself now I know there was a lot of students down there a lot of my friends that took other degrees that didn't work too hard I don't know how it worked out for them
And the emphasis always was on the real world, wasn't it?
That's right.
Not the theoretical, but the real.
Texas A&M represented to me the opportunity for relatively modest people to achieve a goal and a dream that I don't think we could have gotten anywhere.
In terms of building that spirit, we mentioned Silver Taps.
Muster, do you remember Aggie Muster when you were?
Where was it held?
Let's see.
Sometimes I know MSC Steps.
That's where it was, MSC Steps, early on.
Since you graduated, have you gone to Muster's?
No.
I mean, I've gone to musters here.
That's what I mean.
No, no.
Yeah, yeah.
Okay.
I'm going to do the one this spring.
That's what you told me you were going to do.
I'm looking forward to it.
I don't know anybody else that does anything like that.
I don't think so.
In the world.
I think A&M probably at least makes a big attempt to stay closer to its students.
It's kind of ironic.
I kind of irritated Diana.
You may have probably never heard this story, but when I was in office, their athletic budget was in huge trouble.
She had borrowed, I think, several million dollars out of the student activity and the state auditor that was on their way out.
So she and some of my friends who had graduated, Bob Hoy and those, came down to see me and
We would like for the city to give us, and I may be wrong about the number, it was a sizable number, out of some funds we had, a grant in effect to cover the shortage.
And I thought about it.
for a while and then in the end I talked to the council about it and they weren't too interested because legally we couldn't do it.
And she was pretty upset about it, but at the time I told her, I said, you know Diana, do you have a list of your ex-students?
She said no.
I said do you ever ask them for money?
No.
I said, you know I think it's a little bit improper to come to ask the citizens of this city when you're not even asking your own graduates for money.
Now, as far as I know, that is a unique reality for A&M.
These events that join it together, including Muster, and then for you commencement.
Who came to commencement when you got your degree?
Well, when I graduated the first time, my parents came and a number of my aunts and uncles from the family, part of the family in San Antonio.
How did you feel walking across that stage?
Oh, I think, I mean, you know, I've made it.
I have not let my family down.
And was it special to hear your name called?
and your hand shaking.
That's right.
Not get it in the mail.
That's right, that's right.
It was there in your hand.
Commencement in your day was held in G. Raleigh?
Yes, it was.
They had just built G. Raleigh.
Big.
Big, big.
Before then, I guess, I don't know where it was held, in Guyon?
I think so.
And what we couldn't think of the other day was P.L.
Downs.
Was it the Downs?
No, that's an auditorium.
No, the Downs, not an auditorium, was a swimming deal.
Yeah, yeah, that's not the old.
No, it's not the old basketball game.
Well, did you feel that you were, when you graduated, you feel reasonably well prepared to be a real engineer?
I thought I could lick the world.
And you stayed on to do a graduate degree.
Why?
I thought that I really wanted to get a little more specialization.
The electrical engineering department in those days gave you a pretty broad background, both power and electronics, as they called it.
At the time I graduated the first time, I was prepared to go to GE, which I, by the way, did when I graduated.
and reported to building one steam turbine.
But I knew from day one I didn't want to be a power engineer.
But my dad wanted me to do that.
And I was only there three months until I had to report to the Air Force.
And I never went back.
So I decided the best thing I'd do is get a master's degree.
You did a thesis and you did a project in those days.
And that's what I wanted to do.
By the time you finished that master's degree, were you planning on being a self-employed engineer?
You know, the day I finished there, I wasn't sure exactly what I wanted to do.
I just knew that I was going to be self-employed.
I didn't think I was going to be working for somebody.
We've already asked this in a different way.
What creates Aggie spirit, and why are Aggies so loyal?
Well, I think it's the way they are indoctrinated, the way they relate to each other for the four or five years they're there.
the the system the program at a m everything you do builds loyalty comradeship integrity hard work i think it's those things all put together
If you were to go to City College in New York, right, you would not see your classmates except in class, and then you'd go home and you'd never see them again.
You could go to the University of Texas.
There you'd see your classmates a little more, but there would not be any program to keep you together, to relate to each other, to depend on each other.
That's very, very true.
All right, this is probably saying the same thing.
What did you learn at A&M that has had a strong effect on your life?
Well, I think the things that I just related.
I think hard work, integrity,
I guess comradeship to a certain extent.
But I think those, I think.
All right, if you were the consultant,
selected to come in and advise the A&M decision makers today about what they should do more of or less of in the future to keep A&M moving forward.
What advice would you give them?
Well, I think A&M is faced with, you know, several problems.
I think they've done, in my opinion, almost everything right.

I think their political skills are abysmal and I don't think you can live in this world and relate to Austin and Washington because unfortunately more and more of your success or failure depends on and I think we've got to do a better job relating with the political structure.
You can't sit in College Station and say they can't touch me and I'm not going to worry about them.
That's true.
I think the university, and this is damned if they do, damned if they don't, the university is going to have to recognize the Hispanic population in the state.
When you look at the population, and I think A&M has been, because it is so homogeneous,
They've been able to set goals and stick with them.
That's been the positive side.
Whereas if you have this diverse population, you have too many different directions that people are tugging to go in.
So their own success may be their own failure ultimately.
They're going to have to recognize that Hispanic population, especially in relation to Austin and Washington.
And I don't know.
I think once they become more diverse down there, they're going to start having problems they haven't had before.
And I don't think you're going to have the things we've talked about for two or three hours are going to have the significance or the impact that they used to.
And that's sad, too.

uh got a couple more serious questions but before we get to that do you have a favorite aggie story amusing or serious or goofy or any any good bull that you remember you know i haven't thought about this in so long oh i

some joke that you and some other guys play you mentioned the the the other night the other morning you mentioned the uh steam tunnel and dumping the oh oh yeah but i think everybody did that uh what about uh babo bombs or putting something in somebody's room did well i do remember putting uh we used to um you could you could break the glass off of a regular incandescent bulb
and you could tie a firecracker to the filament if it didn't break.
Then you could put it inside a paper sack filled with flour.
That took some engineering.
When you turned on the light switch, kaboom, flour went everywhere.
Oh, I've not heard of that one before.
Probably why you haven't, it took a lot of work.
Did that ever happen in your outfit?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Alright, then who got to clean the room up?
The freshmen?
Well, first they had to find out who they thought did it.
This happened actually in my sophomore year, and it took a while to build the thing.
And I imagine some guys hadn't cleaned it up.
Those of us that might have been involved were long gone to the movie.
We weren't around to be found.
What about a serious Aggie story?
Do you have a heart touching one?
Well, I'm sure there was.
I thought those two Aggies had crashed their plane on the drill field at the bonfire, those two Hensons.
That was a tragic situation.
Did you know about the existence of secret fraternities when you were there?
Oh, that was all over, all over the place.
The TTs, and they disbanded them my junior year.
I never knew about them really until it all of a sudden it boiled up in the battalion.
What about the stickers?
Did you know about them?
No, I didn't know anything about them.
I never knew anything about that they even existed until it was in the battalion.
If you were to make a major gift to Texas A&M, for what purpose would you want that gift used?
I think for the electrical engineering department.
What would you want them to do?
Whatever they decided to do with it.
And why do you feel that grateful to electrical engineering?
Well, I think whatever success I had came from there.
This is next to the last one.
To what A&M former students, faculty, friends do you feel most grateful and why?
Well, like I said, I feel a tremendous amount of gratitude to the electrical engineering faculty, to the college as a whole.
And then I have people like Joe Walker, who was a classmate of mine at A&M.
I just think that the experience there is, people are lucky to have been able to partake of.
Last question.
What feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M?
Oh, a tremendous amount of love and respect.
I mean, people, I think it's expressed best with, you know, it's a religion almost.
And people don't understand that.
That's a good point to put on.
